Republic County Schools
September 4 at 2:31 AM ·

USD #109 has been approved to provide a free breakfast and lunch to all students enrolled in the district, no matter their eligibility status, until further notice through the USDA school food service program starting Tuesday, September 8. In addition, anyone 1-18 years of age in the community is also eligible for the free meals. If you are not enrolled and wish to receive meals, please contact the district office for additional information starting Tuesday morning at 785-527-5621.

Any questions regarding this program should be directed to Mr. Lyder at llyder@usd109.org.

If you have not already done so, it is still crucial to complete a free/reduced lunch application as when this program ends you will be charged at your respected eligibility status price.

USD #109 is an equal opportunity employer and does not determine the end date of the program.

shared_text:
Harvey County Parents as Teachers
August 31 at 1:00 PM ·

Activity of the Week!
Peek-A-Boo Board
For this activity, you will need colorful felt or cloth (several pieces), scissors, glue gun & glue sticks, a large piece of foam board or large piece of cardboard, and animal photos (or animal flashcards). To get started, cut several pieces of felt or cloth to fit the size of my animal flashcards/pictures. Then prepare the board by gluing the zoo animal flashcards around on the white foam board. Next, grab the glue gun and glue each rectangle on top of its matching zoo animal flashcard. Only put glue along the very top edge of the rectangle so that the felt stays secure to the board and you can still lift up the felt to easily to see the animals. Once the glue is dry allow your child to come and play. Encourage them to search for specific animals and talk with them about the animals they find.
https://toddlerapproved.com/2014/07/zoo-animal-peek-boo-board.html

Harvey County Parents as Teachers
July 20 at 1:00 PM ·

Activity of the Day!
Holey TP Roll Threading
For this activity, you will need cardboard tubes, straws (or similar), a hole puncher, and scissors. Cut each of the cardboard tubes in half or about 10 – 15cm long. punch holes into the cardboard tubes using the hole puncher. Present your child with the straws and ask them to thread them through the holes in the cardboard tube. In one side and out the other. This activity challenges your child’s fine motor and problem solving skills!
https://laughingkidslearn.com/fine-motor-threading-activity-using-straws-and-cardboard-tubes/

A Book Walk is coming to Clyde! Randolph-Decker will have the book , Dog's Colorful Day, in Clyde's business windows from Monday, June 29 until July 6 for children to stroll downtown and enjoy the book. Afterward the child's information form can be turned back into the Library and they will receive tickets to possibly win a prize on the last day of Summer Reading on July 31. Please call the Library at 446-3563 with any questions!

Harvey County Parents as Teachers
May 29 at 1:00 PM ·

Activity of the Day!
Ice Play
The idea behind this invitation to play is to freeze interesting items inside blocks of ice for your children to release and explore. For this activity, you will need water, containers such as ice cube trays, small cups, plastic bowls, balloons, etc., and small toys large enough not to pose a choking hazard for your child. Place water and the small items into containers. Place the containers into the freezer until frozen solid. Once the items are frozen take your child outside and provide them with pipettes, or a squeeze filled with warm water to help rescue the items inside the ice. You can also provide items for chipping and hammering the ice: spoons, scoops, toy tools, and safety goggles. Encourage your child to try different methods of releasing their toys and them to play as long as they are interested!

Laundry Basket Skee Ball

Affinity Consulting
May 19 at 11:01 AM ·

Tip Tuesdays
PDF of visual posted at www.AffinityConsulting.info
Alright parents, there have been a lot of on-line 'tips' for eveyone as we stay at home. We talk a lot about the behaviour of the kids but let's take a moment and talk about yours....
Some of you may be ready for a little check in, so I made you a chart. That's right a chart for the parents! It's a check in to remind you that your kids take their lead from you. Just like we help the kids track what they are doing here is one for you. You can put whatever is important to you on your list. Have a moment to do something silly with your child during changing time? Great! After you change your child try this #VroomTip. Puff up your cheeks like a blowfish & then place their feet on your cheeks to push the air out until you go "pop!" This game may be silly, but it's not! Your child learns to watch & respond, which are important to communication. Stopping for a little silly is always good.

For more Vroom Tips, to download the Vroom App, or to sign up for Vroom By Text visit: https://www.vroom.org/

Activity of the Day!
Coloring Inside a Box
For this activity, you will need a large box and your choice of coloring materials ie crayons, markers, colored pencils, etc. Set up the box so that your child can easily get in and out of it. Encourage your child to color on the inside and outside of the box. Color with them and ask them open-ended questions about their drawings! “Can you tell me what is happening in this picture?” “What is your favorite thing about what you have drawn?”

Harvey County Parents as Teachers
April 8 at 1:00 PM ·

Activity of the Day!
Dinosaur Rescue Bin
For this activity, you will need a sensory bin or large tub, rice, a giant bowl, a slotted spoon, an icecube tray, and mini dinosaurs or other small animals. Start with the big sensory bin and add in the giant bowl. Mix the mini dinosaurs and the rice together – making sure to really hide the dinosaurs down deep. Next to the bowl, place the ice cube tray as the “keeper” of the dinosaurs once they are scooped out. Show your child how to use the slotted spoon to find the dinosaurs, scoop them out, and transfer them to their ice cube tray.

Need something to keep your toddler busy for a few minutes? Try this fun idea. All you need is an empty paper towel or toilet paper roll and some ponytail holders. Put the hair bands onto the tube and let your child take them off. They can also try to put them back on. Great problem solving work!
(P.S. Using rubber bands instead is discouraged as they might snap little fingers.)

shared_text:
YOUTUBE.COM
Beat & Repeat

Vroom
April 7 at 5:01 PM ·

Early learning happens at home. Due to the impact of COVID-19 many families are now spending more time at home together. We're offering Vroom Tip videos every Tuesday at 10am to help add early learning into your new daily routine. Parents and caregivers YOU already have what it takes to create a bright future for your child!

#VroomTip: Play "Beat and Repeat" anywhere. Create a rhythmic beat with two claps. Can your child copy it? Repeat until they get it. Have them create their own rhythm with two claps. Anytime someone misses, try again. Then make it three beats. How many beats can you get to? Four? Five? Six?

#BrainyBackground: Your child develops self-control as they copy your patterns or create their own. If they make a mistake, all the better. They learn that mistakes are a necessary part of learning—a good lesson no matter how old you are! https://youtu.be/Auns4tHyXes

shared_text:
ZEROTOTHREE.ORG
Young Children at Home during the COVID-19 Outbreak: The Importance of Self-Care

Vroom
April 2 at 5:26 PM ·

When your child seems fussy, Use this #VroomTip. Try singing a rhyme or a song. Do they calm down when your voice is quiet, or do they respond to big facial expressions and an enthusiastic voice? Try different rhymes and songs to find their favorites.

#BrainyBackground: When you respond to your child’s movements and sounds, you build a trusting relationship that supports future learning. You also teach them ways to deal with stress while building a love of language.

Early learning happens at home. Due to the impact of COVID-19 many families now spending more time at home together. ZERO TO THREE shares why stress relief and self-care should be an important part of your new at-home routine. https://www.zerotothree.org/resources/3262-young-children-at-home-during-the-covid-19-outbreak-the-importance-of-self-care

post_text: Notice to Republic County Residents
shared_text:
Ronald W. Blad
March 31 at 6:23 PM ·

Notice to Republic County Residents:
As you know, the Governor issued a "Stay A Home" Order effective yesterday (3/30/2020).

If the County Health Department has personally advised you to quarantine, you must stay home. If you do not comply with the quarantine, you can be cited with a Class C misdemeanor. This can result in a fine of up to $500.00.

If you violate the Governor's "Stay At Home" Order, that is a Class A misdemeanor. This can result in a fine up to $2,500 and up to 1 year in jail.

Yesterday I froze water in a bunch of baggies and a balloon and I tried to freeze a glove (a hand shaped glacier!) because I thought it would be fun to have different shapes of colored ice in a water table tub. shared_text:
YOUTUBE.COM
Baby Conversations

Vroom
March 24 at 5:01 PM ·

Early learning happens at home. Due to the impact of COVID-19 many families now spending more time at home together. We're offering Vroom Tip videos every Tuesday at 10am to help add early learning into your new daily routine. Parents and caregivers YOU already have what it takes to create a bright future for your child!

Baby conversations can take place anytime, like feeding time. Use this #VroomTip to start the conversation by describing what you think your baby wants. Conversations go both ways, so watch how your baby responds to you without words and keep the conversation going. You can show babies new ways of communicating. Like making a sign or gesture for milk.

#BrainyBackground: When you listen to what your baby is telling you and respond back, with or without words you are having a real conversation. Even before babies can say words themselves, they are learning what words mean and how to communicate all while strengthening your bond. https://youtu.be/GvvVoN2xekY

March 18 at 6:12 PM ·

March 18, 2020

Dear Parents and Guardians:

USD 426 will be starting a food service program on Monday, March 23, 2020 for children aged 1 to 18. We will be serving both breakfast and lunch with pick-up at the following locations and times:
Courtland-Elementary School-11:00 a.m.-11:30 a.m.
Scandia-City Park-12:00 p.m.-12:30 p.m.
Republic-City Park-12:00 p.m.-12:30 p.m.
Formoso-City Park-12:00 p.m.-12:30 p.m.
*Children eating have to be present to pick up their meals. If they are not present, the meal will not be provided.
*You will not be allowed inside any facility to pick up your meal.
*Do not gather at the locations, remain in your vehicles, keeping your social distancing.

If you want a meal you will need to call (785) 374-4221 by Friday, March 20, 2020 by 12:00 p.m. if you are wanting lunch for Monday, March 23, 2020. Call in by 12:00 p.m. by Friday for the next week's meals.

You will receive lunch for the day and breakfast for the following day.

Sincerely,

Steve Joonas
Superintendent
Pike Valley USD 426

shared_text:
Vroom
January 3 at 11:53 AM ·

A baby’s brain is wired to grow from birth! It starts off with billions of neurons. During your child’s earliest years, their brain makes 1 million neural connections every single second.

That’s a lot of brain building! Positive, supportive experiences with adults help your child’s brain grow strong and flexible. That makes you your child’s #1 brain builder! Use the science of early learning to help your child succeed and thrive. https://www.vroom.org/science

LATIMES.COM
What makes a good story? It may not be what you think

Vroom
December 16, 2019 at 11:51 AM ·

Sorting the laundry? Use this #VroomTip to encourage your child to help you find all of the socks and make a pile of them. Pick a sock and make up a story, pretending it is a puppet looking for its matching friend. Celebrate when you find a match. Then let them take a turn as the puppet.

#BrainyBackground: Not only is this activity fun, but your child makes connections as they group the socks and look for the matching pairs. They must use focus and self-control to remember the details of the matching sock. When they pretend, they're thinking creatively.

Learn more about what makes a good child's story.

DEVELOPINGCHILD.HARVARD.EDU
Play in Early Childhood: The Role of Play in Any Setting

Vroom
December 13, 2019 at 2:08 PM ·

Talk with your child as you move around the room for this #VroomTip. Tell them, “Here I am!” Do they move their eyes? Turn or lift their head to look for you? When they find you, give them a big smile, again saying, “Here I am!”

#BrainyBackground: Your child is interested in you, and from birth on they're able to follow what they see and hear. As they track you, reinforce this discovery by telling them where you are.

Center on the Developing Child at Harvard University shares more on the importance of play in early learning.

PBS.ORG
Social Skills: Friendship at Age 3 | Milestones | PBS KIDS for Parents

Vroom
December 6, 2019 at 11:54 AM ·

Do a photo tour around your home with this #VroomTip. Talk with your child about the photographs you see. Have a conversation with them about the stories behind the pictures—about the person and what he or she was doing at the time.

#BrainyBackground: Sharing stories about the people—family and friends—who are important to you is a great way for your child to learn who they are and to feel valued. You can make this into a tradition and do it often. Back and forth conversations will also promote their literacy skills.

PBS KIDS shares more ways to help your child develop social skills to build friendships.

BBC.CO.UK
Four top tips for talking to your baby

Vroom
November 12, 2019 at 2:08 PM ·

Is your child starting to babble? Use this #VroomTip at bath time as an opportunity to babble about the letter B. If they say, “ba,” you can say, “Baby takes a bath with bubbles! Ba-ba-ba!” If they respond with more babbles, copy them right back! What other words can you make from their babbling sounds?

#BrainyBackground: You’re helping your child develop communication skills when you respond to their sounds with sounds of your own, building on their babbling to create words. They're also learning to engage in the back and forth conversations that are basic to relationships and learning.

BBC shares more ways to babble with your child to promote language skills.

PBS.ORG
Helping Children With Sharing | Parenting Tips & Advice | PBS KIDS for Parents

Vroom
November 8, 2019 at 4:12 PM ·

Encourage sharing and taking turns with this #VroomTip. Ask your child to feed you! After they take a bite say, “My turn!” Open your mouth and see if they'll give you a bite. Say, “Thank you!” and then prompt them to take a turn. They will love having a turn at being in charge!

#BrainyBackground: When you and your child take turns, you're modeling the back-and-forth of communication, which will help them as they learn to talk and read. They're also learning about relating to others in a fun way.

PBS KIDS shares more tips to promote sharing and kindness.

shared_text:
MOTHER.LY
It’s science: How your child’s social skills set the stage for success

Vroom
October 25, 2019 at 2:58 PM ·

When you’re in the park, use this #VroomTip to take turns with your child making different sounds with your voices, hands and feet. Stomp really loud or clap your hands up high. When they make a sound, imitate it and then make a new one. How many different sounds can you two make?

#BrainyBackground: Sound Makers gives your child practice focusing and controlling their behavior. To copy your sound, they have to pay attention and remember it. Waiting for their turn takes self-control. Your child will need these thinking skills in school, work, and life.

Motherly shares how helping your child learn to control their behavior can help them build social skills.

#BrainyBackground: Sound Makers gives your child practice focusing and controlling their behavior. To copy your sound, they have to pay attention and remember it. Waiting for their turn takes self-control. Your child will need these thinking skills in school, work, and life.

Motherly shares how helping your child learn to control their behavior can help them build social skills.
